\begin_layout Standard
Classification of differential equations provide intuition about the physical process that the equation describes, as well as providing context we use as we go about solving the equation. A differential equation can be classified as either ordinary or partial, linear or non-linear, and by its homogeneity and equation order. These are described briefly below, with examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Ordinary and Partial Differential Equations —
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary classification we use to organize types of differential equations is whether they are 
\shape italic
ordinary
\shape default
 or 
\shape italic
partial
\shape default
 differential equations. 
\emph on
Ordinary differential equations
\emph default
 (ODEs) involve functions of a single variable. All derivatives present in the ODE are relative to that one variable. Partial differential equations are functions of more than one variable and the partial derivatives of these functions are taken with respect to those variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of an ODE is shown in Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RLC"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. This equation has two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $q(t)$
\end_inset

 (charge) and 
\begin_inset Formula $V(t)$
\end_inset

 (voltage), the values of which depend on time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. All of the derivatives are with respect the independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 are constants. 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}	
	L \FullDiff{2}{q(t)}{t} + R \FullDiff{}{q(t)}{t} + \frac{1}{C} q(t) = V(t) \label{eq:RLC}
\end{align}
\end_inset

This general example describes the flow of charge as a function of time in a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "RLC circuit"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RLC_circuit"
literal "false"

\end_inset

with an applied voltage that changes with time. Other examples of ODEs you may encounter in the MSE core include ODEs for grain growth as a function of time and the equations of motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Partial differential equations
\emph default
 (PDEs) contain multivariable functions and their partial derivatives i.e., a derivative with respect to one variable with others held constant. As physical phenomenon often vary in both space and time, PDEs — and methods of solving them — will be encountered in many of the core MSE courses. These phenomena include wave behavior, diffusion, the Schödinger equation, heat conduction, the Cahn-Hilliard equation, and many others. A typical example of a PDEs you will encounter is Fick's Second Law. In 1D, this is: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\Partial{}{\varphi(x,t)}{t} = D\Partial{2}{\varphi(x,t)}{x} \label{eq:Ficks2}
\end{align}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is the concentration as a function of position 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. This expression equates the change in the concentration over time to the shape (concavity) of the concentration profile. Partial differential equations are, by nature, often more difficult to solve than ODEs, but, as with ODEs, there exist simple, analytic, and systematic methods for solving many of these equations. 
\end_layout

