\begin_layout Paragraph
Linearity —
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While considering how to solve a differential equation, it is crucial to consider whether an equation is linear or non-linear. For example, an ODE like that represented in Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LagrangeNote"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is linear if the 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a linear function of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $f, f', f\prime\prime...f^{(n)}$
\end_inset

. This definition also applies to PDEs. The expression for the general linear ODE of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%						
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	a_0(x)f^{(n)}+a_1(x)f^{(n-1)} + ... + a_n(x)f = g(t) \label{eq:LinearODE}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%			
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

Any expression that is not of this form is considered 
\shape italic
nonlinear
\shape default
. The presence of a product such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\cdot f\prime$
\end_inset

, a power such as 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\prime)^2$
\end_inset

, or a sinusoidal function of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 would make the equation nonlinear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The methods of solving linear differential equations are well-developed. Nonlinear differential equations, on the other hand, often require more complex analysis. As you will see, methods of 
\shape italic
linearization
\shape default
 (small-angle approximations, stability theory) as well as numerical techniques are powerful ways to approach these problems.
\end_layout

