\end_inset

 In this section, we use Sturm-Liouville theory in solving a separable, linear, second-order homogeneous partial differential equation. Sturm-Liouville theory can be used on differential equations (here, in 1D) of the form: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\FullDiff{}{}{x}\Big[p(x)\FullDiff{}{y}{x}\Big]-q(x)y+\lambda r(x)y = 0 \label{eq:SturmLiouville}
	\intertext{or}
	\big[p(x)y\prime]\prime-q(x)y+\lambda r(x)y = 0 \label{eq:SturmLiouville-2}
\end{align}
\end_inset

This type of problem requires knowledge of many use of many concepts and techniques in solving ODEs, including 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sec:SepVar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, Fundamental Solutions of Linear First- and Second-Order Homogeneous Equations, Fourier Series, and Orthogonal Solution Functions. It is important to note that the approach described below (adapted from JJ Hoyt's 
\shape italic
Phase Transformations
\shape default
), which employs separation of variables and Fourier transforms, works only on linear equations. A different approach must be taken for non-linear equations (such as Cahn-Hilliard).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use the example of a solid slab of material of length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 that has a constant concentration of some elemental species at time zero 
\begin_inset Formula $ \varphi(x,0) = \varphi_0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 within the slab. On either end of the slab we have homogeneous boundary conditions defining the surface concentrations fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0,t) = \varphi(L,t) = 0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. The changing concentration profile, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is dictated by Fick's second law, as described earlier in Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ficks2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
