	\intertext{or, in shorthand,}
	\varphi &= TX
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It isn't clear why we do this at this point, but stay tuned. Combining Eqs. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ficks2-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SepVar-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	XT\prime = DTX\prime\prime
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the primed Lagrange notation denotes total derivatives. 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are functions only of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, respectively. Now, we separate the variables completely to acquire:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	\frac{1}{DT}T\prime = \frac{1}{X}X\prime\prime
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This representation conveys something critical: each side of the equation must be equal to 
\emph on
the same
\emph default
 constant. This is because the two sides of the equation are equal to each other and the only way a collection of time-dependent quantities can be equivilent to a selection of position-dependent quantities is for them to be constant with respect to both time and position. We select this constant — for reasons that become clear of the convience of this selection later in the analysis — as 
\begin_inset Formula $-\lambda^2$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%Show and example here?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
		\frac{1}{DT}T\prime &= -\lambda^2 \label{eq:SepT}\\
		\frac{1}{X}X\prime\prime &= -\lambda^2 \label{eq:SepX}
	\end{align}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Integration of Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SepT"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 yields, from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sec:SepVar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\frac{1}{DT}T\prime &= -\lambda^2 \nonumber\\
	\frac{1}{T}\FullDiff{}{T}{t} &= -\lambda^2 D \nonumber\\
	\int \frac{1}{T}\Diff{}{T} &= -\int \lambda^2 D \Diff{}{t} \nonumber\\
	\ln{T} &= -\lambda^2 D t + T_0 \nonumber\\
	\intertext{where $T_0$ is the combined constant of integration:}
	T = T(t) &= \exp{(-\lambda^2 D t + T_0)} \nonumber\\
	T(t) &= T_0 \exp{(-\lambda^2 D t)} \label{eq:Tt}
\end{align}
\end_inset

Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SepX"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, on the other hand, is a linear, homogeneous, second-order ODE with constant coefficients that describes simple harmonic behavior. We can solve this by assessing its 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "characteristic equation"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristic_equation_(calculus)"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	r^2+\lambda^2 = 0\\
	\intertext{which has roots:}
	r = \pm \lambda i
\end{align}
\end_inset

When the roots of the characteristic equation are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $r = \alpha \pm \beta i$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "solution of the differential equation (Pg. 5)"
target "http://www.stewartcalculus.com/data/CALCULUS\%20Concepts\%20and\%20Contexts/upfiles/3c3-2ndOrderLinearEqns_Stu.pdf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

is: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
		y = e^{\alpha x}(c_1 \cos{\beta x} + c_2 \sin{\beta x})
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha = 0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta = \lambda$
\end_inset

, so our solution is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	X = X(x) = \tilde{A} \cos{\lambda x} + \tilde{B} \sin{\lambda x} \label{eq:Xx}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}$
\end_inset

 are constants that will be further simplified later. Recalling Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SepVar-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and utilizing our results from Eqs. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Tt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Xx"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we find: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\varphi(x,y) &= X(x)T(x) = T_0 \big[\tilde{A} \cos{\lambda x} + \tilde{B} \cos{\lambda x}\big]\exp{(-\lambda^2 D t)}\\
	\intertext{where we now define $T_0 \tilde{A} = A$ and $T_0 \tilde{B} = B$ to get:}
	\varphi(x,y) &= X(x)T(x) = \big[A\cos{\lambda x} + B\sin{\lambda x}\big]\exp{(-\lambda^2 D t)} \label{eq:DiffSol}
\end{align}
\end_inset

Physially, this solution begins to make sense. At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 we have a constant concentration, but concentration begins to decay esponentially with time as 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 are all positive, real constants. The concentration profile is a linear combination of sine and cosine functions, which does not yet yield any physical intuition for this system as we have yet to utilize boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall at this point that we have not specified any value for the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, as is typical when solving this type of Sturm-Liouville problem. This suggests that there are possible solutions for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_n$
\end_inset

. The Principle of Superposition dictates, then, that if Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffSol"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is a solution, the complete solution to the problem is a summation of all possible solutions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\Aboxed{\varphi(x,y) = 	\sum_{n=1}^\infty \big[A_n\cos{\lambda_n x} + B_n\sin{\lambda_n x}\big]\exp{(-\lambda_n^2 D t)}} \label{eq:DiffSolFull}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 influences the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, these values must also be calculated for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, to completely solve our well-posed boundary value problem, we utilize our boundary conditions: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
		\varphi(0,t) &= 0\, \quad t \geq 0 \label{eq:Boundx0}\\
		\varphi(L,t) &= 0\, \quad t \geq 0 \label{eq:BoundxL}\\
		\varphi(x,0) &= \varphi_0\, \quad 0<x<L \label{eq:Time0}
	\end{align}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 At 
\begin_inset Formula $x = 0$
\end_inset

, the sine term in Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffSolFull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is zero, and therefore the boundary condition in Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Boundx0"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can only be satisfied at all t if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_n = 0$
\end_inset

. At 
\begin_inset Formula $x = L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin{\lambda_n x}$
\end_inset

 must be zero for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_n$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_n = n\pi/L$
\end_inset

. We need only solve now for 
\begin_inset Formula $B_n$
\end_inset

 using the intial condition, Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Time0"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using our values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_n$
\end_inset

 and assessing Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffSolFull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	\varphi_0 = \sum_{n=1}^\infty B_n \sin{\frac{n \pi x}{L}} \label{eq:Time0-1}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we must recognized the orthogonal property of the sine function, which states that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	\int_0^L \sin{\frac{n \pi x}{L}} \sin{\frac{m \pi x}{L}}
	   \begin{cases}
      = 0, & \text{if}\ n\neq m \\
     \neq 0, & \text{if}\ n = m
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can test this graphically using a plotting program if you like — the integrated value of this product is only non-zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m$
\end_inset

 — or you can follow the proof 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "http://www.math.umd.edu/~psg/401/ortho.pdf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. We can multiply both sides of the Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Time0-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin{n \pi x/L}$
\end_inset

, then, and integrate both sides from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
		\varphi_0 \int_0^L\sin{\frac{m \pi x}{L}} &= \int_0^L \sum_{n=1}^\infty \big[B_n \sin{\frac{n \pi x}{L}} \sin{\frac{m \pi x}{L}}\big] \nonumber
		\intertext{After integration, the only term that survives on the right-hand side is the $m=n$ term, and therefore:}
		\varphi_0 \int_0^L\sin{\frac{n \pi x}{L}} &= B_n\int_0^L \sin{\frac{n \pi x}{L}}^2 \nonumber\\
		\varphi_0 \int_0^L\sin{\frac{n \pi x}{L}} &= \frac{B_n L}{4} \big[2- \frac{\sin{2 n \pi}}{n \pi} \big] \nonumber\\
		\intertext{the $\sin{2 n \pi}$ term is always zero:}
		\varphi_0 \int_0^L\sin{\frac{n \pi x}{L}} &= \frac{B_n L}{2} \nonumber\\
		2 \frac{\varphi_0}{L} \int_0^L\sin{{n \pi x}{L}} &= B_n \nonumber\\
		B_n  &= 2 \frac{\varphi_0}{L} \big[\frac{L}{n \pi}(1-\cos{n \pi})\big] \nonumber\\
		\Aboxed{B_n  &= 2 \frac{\varphi_0}{n \pi} (1-\cos{n \pi})}
	\end{align}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For even values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $B_n$
\end_inset

 constant is zero. For odd values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_n = \frac{4 \varphi_0}{n \pi}$
\end_inset

. We utilize the values we acquired for 
\begin_inset Formula $A_n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and plug them into Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffSolFull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. A change in summation index to account for the 
\begin_inset Formula $B_n$
\end_inset

 values yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\Aboxed{\varphi(x,t) = \frac{4 c_0}{\pi} \sum_{k=0}^\infty \frac{1}{2k+1} \sin{\frac{(2k+1)\pi x}{L}}\exp{\Big[-\big(\frac{(2k+1)\pi}{L}\big)^2 Dt\Big]}}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This summation converges quickly. We now have the ability to calculate the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,t)$
\end_inset

 at any position 
\begin_inset Formula $0 < x < L$
\end_inset

 and time 
\begin_inset Formula $t > 0$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

