Paul Shewman's 
\shape italic
Diffusion in Solids
\shape default
. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
J.W. Brown and R.V. Churchill's 
\shape italic
Fourier Series and Boundary Values Problems
\shape default
, 6
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Edition. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary goal behind the Fourier transform is to solve a differential equation with some unknown function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

. We apply the transform (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

) to convert the function into something that can be solved more easily: 
\begin_inset Formula $f \xrightarrow{\mathscr{F}} F$
\end_inset

. The transformed function is often also represented using a 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}$
\end_inset

. We solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and then perform an inverse Fourier transform (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}^{-1}$
\end_inset

) to recover the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that Fourier 
\shape italic
series
\shape default
 — which are used to when working with periodic functions — can be generalized to Fourier integral transforms (or Fourier transforms) when the period of the function becomes infinitely long. Let's begin with the Fourier series an build on our results from our discussion above where we found that a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 defined on some finite interval 
\begin_inset Formula $x \in[0,L]$
\end_inset

 and vanishing at the boundaries, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0) = f(L) = 0$
\end_inset

 can be expanded as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffSolFull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following derivation is adapted from Olmstead and Volpert. In general, we can attempt to represent 
\shape italic
any
\shape default
 function that is periodic over period 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,L]$
\end_inset

 with a Fourier series of form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f(x) = a_0 + \sum_{n=1}^\infty\left[a_n \cos{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}} + b_n \sin{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}}\right]
\label{eq:GenSol}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, we need to know how to find the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_n$
\end_inset

 for this representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

. For this analysis we must utilize the following integral identities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%Kronecker delta?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_0^L{\sin{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}}\cos{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}}}dx= 0 \quad n,m = 1,2,3,...,
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_0^L{\cos{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}}\cos{\frac{2 \pi m x}{L}}} dx= 
	\begin{cases}
		0, \text{\,if} \quad n,m = 1,2,3,..., n\neq m\\
		L/2, \text{\,if} \quad n = m = 1,2,3,...,\\
	\end{cases}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_0^L{\sin{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}}\sin{\frac{2 \pi m x}{L}}} dx = 
	\begin{cases}
		0, \text{\,if} \quad  n,m = 1,2,3,..., n\neq m\\
		L/2, \text{\,if} \quad n = m = 1,2,3,...,\\
	\end{cases}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_0^L{\cos{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}}} dx = 
	\begin{cases}
		0, \text{\,if} \quad n,m = 1,2,3,...,\\
		L, \text{\,if} \quad n = 0\\
	\end{cases}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_0^L{\sin{\frac{2 \pi n x}{L}}} dx = 
		0, \text{\,if} \quad n,m = 0,1,2,3,...,\\
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These identities state the orthogonal properties of sines and cosines that will be used to derive the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_n$
\end_inset

. Recall that two functions are orthogonal on an interval if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_a^b f(x)g(x)dx = 0
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can therefore multiply Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GenSol"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}}$
\end_inset

 (note 
\begin_inset Formula $n = 1$
\end_inset

) and integrate over 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,L]$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	\int_0^L f(x)\cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx &= a_0 \int_0^L \cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx +\\
	&a_1 \int_0^L \cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} \cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx +b_1 \int_0^L \sin{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx +\\
	&a_2 \int_0^L \cos{\frac{4 \pi x}{L}} \cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx +b_2 \int_0^L \sin{\frac{4 \pi x}{L}} cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx + ...\\
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying the orthogonal properties of the integral products finds that all terms on the right-hand side of this equation are zero apart from the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_1$
\end_inset

 term. The equation therefore reduces to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_0^L f(x)\cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx = a_1 \int_0^L \cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx= a_1\frac{L}{2}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \[a_1 = \frac{2}{L} \int_0^L f(x)\cos{\frac{2 \pi x}{L}} dx\]
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other Fourier coefficients can be solved for in a similar manner, which yields the general solutions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
	a_0 &= \frac{1}{L} \int_0^L f(x)\\
		a_n &= \frac{2}{L} \int_0^L f(x)\cos{\frac{2 n \pi x}{L}}dx \quad (n = 1,2,3...)\\
			b_n &= \frac{2}{L} \int_0^L f(x)\sin{\frac{2 n \pi x}{L}}dx\quad (n = 1,2,3...)
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To this point we've solved, generally, for the coefficients of a Fourier series over a finite interval. This is useful, but we my want to use the full complex form of the Fourier series in later discussion of the Fourier transform. We know that 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Euler's formula"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler's_formula#Relationship_to_trigonometry"
literal "false"

\end_inset

can be used to express trigonometric functions with the complex exponential function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
