\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	f_{L}(x) \sim \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty} c_n e^{i k_n x}
\label{eq:ComplexFourierSeries}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For convenience, we'll define the integral to be 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\frac{L}{2},\frac{L}{2}]$
\end_inset

. The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 notation indicates that the series representation is an approximation, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 represents the period over which the series is applied. The orthogonality condition holds for these complex exponential and its complex conjugate over this interval:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	\int_{-\frac{L}{2}}^{\frac{L}{2}} e^{i k_n x} e^{-i k_m x} dx =
		\begin{cases}
		0, \text{\,if} \quad n \neq m\\
		L, \text{\,if} \quad n = m\\
	\end{cases}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, if we multiply Eq. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ComplexFourierSeries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i k_m x}$
\end_inset

 and solve we find the only term that survives is when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	\int_{-\frac{L}{2}}^{\frac{L}{2}} f_L(x) e^{-i k_m x} dx = L c_m.
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can revert the place-keeping subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and solve for the Fourier coefficients to find:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	 c_n = \frac{1}{L}\int_{-\frac{L}{2}}^{\frac{L}{2}} f_L(x) e^{-i k_n x} dx \quad \text{for\,} n = 0, \pm1, \pm2,...
	\label{eq:FourierComps}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alright, we've defined an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-L/2, L/2]$
\end_inset

, but we want to investigate this interval as 
\begin_inset Formula $L \rightarrow \infty$
\end_inset

 in an attempt to eliminate the periodicity of the Fourier series. If 
\begin_inset Formula $L \rightarrow \infty$
\end_inset

, we know that our function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_L(x)$
\end_inset

 will be non-zero over only a very small range — say an interval of 
\begin_inset Formula $[-a/2, a/2]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a << L$
\end_inset

. This means that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	f_L{x} =
	\begin{cases}
		1 \quad \text{for} |x|<a/2\\
		0 \quad \text{for} a/2 < |x| < L/2
	\end{cases}
\label{eq:Linfty}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This function is zero except for a small bump at the origin of height 1 and width 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

. Let's assess our function over the non-zero interval:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	\int_{-\frac{a}{2}}^{\frac{a}{2}} e^{-i k_n x} dx = \frac{\sin k_n a/2}{k_n L/2} = \frac{\sin n \pi a/L}{n \pi}.
	\label{eq:Thing}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But how does this allow us to consider a continuous Fourier integral transform? Well, we need to consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_L(x)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $L \rightarrow \infty$
\end_inset

. By doing so, we drive all the harmonics of the Fourier function — apart from the central one — out beyond infinity. 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 then has a single bump of width 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 centered at the origin. That is, the separation between the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 harmonics goes to zero, and the representation contains all harmonics. Further, as 
\begin_inset Formula $L \rightarrow \infty$
\end_inset

 we no longer have a periodic function and we can i.e., the fundamental period becomes so large that we no longer have non-periodic function at all. 
